'''Taking Control of your Diabetes (TCOYD)''' is a non-profit ([[501(c)#501.28c.29.283.29|501(c)3]]) educational organization founded in 1995 based in [[Del Mar, California]]. They put on [[Health care]] conferences around the [[United States]], open to anyone who wants to learn more about [[diabetes]].<ref name=tcoydbio>{{Cite web|url=http://tcoyd.org/about-us/about-tcoyd.html|last=Edelman|first=Steven|publisher=TCOYD.org|title=About TCOYD|accessdate=2010-09-25}}</ref> Away from conferences, they publish videos on the [[University of California]]'s [[TV]] station, [[UCTV (University of California)|UCTV]].<ref name=tcoydtv>[http://www.uctv.tv/tcoyd/ TCOYD TV page on UCTV home.] Retrieved 2010-09-25</ref>

==History==
===Creation===
Dr. Steven V. Edelman, MD, who has lives with [[type 1 diabetes]] since age 15, founded the non-profit educational organization in 1995, intending to educate diabetics on how to live healthily with the disease <ref name=tcoydarticle1>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news-medical.net/news/20100610/Diabetes-expert-uses-TCOYD-to-empower-people-take-active-role-in-their-condition.aspx|last=|first=|date= June 10, 2010|accessdate=2010-09-25|publisher=news-medical.net|title=Diabetes expert uses TCOYD to empower people take active role in their condition}}</ref> Over the 15 years of the organizations existence, it has put on over 100 conferences in many cities including [[San Diego]],<ref>[http://tcoyd.org/events/tview_detail/c/26.html San Diego TCOYD conference 2009]</ref> [[Seattle]],<ref>[http://tcoyd.org/national-conferences/san-diego-2007.html Seattle TCOYD Conference 2007]</ref> [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]],<ref>[http://tcoyd.org/national-conferences/providence-2010.html Providence TCOYD Conference 2010]</ref> [[Albequerque]],<ref>[http://tcoyd.org/national-conferences/albuquerque-2009.html Albuquerque TCOYD Conference 2009]</ref> and many more.  Most of the conferences have over 50 health exhibits.

===Television program===
TCOYD has partnered with [[UCTV (University of California)|UCTV]] ([[University of California]] TV) to produce its very own [[television series]]. On the series, experts discuss health issues and give tips on how to stay healthy.<ref name=tcoydarticle1 /> Special guests often appear on the show, Chef Robert Lewis The Happy Diabetic www.happydiabetic.com, and former [[Biggest Loser]] fitness trainer [[Kim Lyons (personal trainer)|Kim Lyons]] and [[Open wheel car]] racer [[Charlie Kimball]].

The organization recently launched a new online reality series titled, "Extreme Diabetes Makeover," which follows seven people with poorly controlled diabetes who, with the help of a "dream team" of diabetes professionals, will take back control and improve their condition.

===Awards and recognition===
Founder Steve Edelman has been very busy since the conception of TCOYD, being a contributor to the [[American Diabetes Association]],<ref name=tcoydarticle2>{{Cite web|url=http://forecast.diabetes.org/news/diabetics-skimp-lifesaving-care-recession|title=Diabetics skimp on lifesaving care in recession|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|coauthors=Edelman, Steven|accessdate=2010-09-25|year=2009}}</ref> he is a professor of medicine at the [[University of California]], he is the Director of Affairs at the Diabetes Care Clinic [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|Veteran Affairs]] Medical Center, and caters to over 4,000 diabetic patients. He has given over 1000 speeches, he had written many books and publications, and frequently appears on television. He was awarded by the American Diabetes Association the 2009 Outstanding Educator in Diabetes Award.<ref name=edelmanbio>[http://tcoyd.org/tcoyd-team/steven-v.-edelman-md.html Steven V. Edelman, MD biography]. Retrieved 2010-09-25</ref> The organization's conferences have been recognized to have top physicians, exhibits with state-of-the-art tools for diabetic management.<ref>[http://news.unchealthcare.org/som-vital-signs/2010/vital-signs-may-13-2010/raleigh-tcoyd-conference-health-fair Raleigh Conference advertisement on the UNC web page]. Retrieved 2010-09-25</ref>

